 -- t10 Unruly Political Uprisings: Migrant Justice Activism in Canada and the United States -- t11 Prejudicial Populists? Evidence from Canada -- tPart four. Global Dimensions of Migration in North America -- t12 Extraction, Dependence, Containment: Questioning Canada’s Role as Immigration and Refugee Norm Entrepreneur -- t13 Development Aid as Migration Control: Comparing Migration Management Aid in Central America and Africa -- t14 Smart Borders and the Diffusion of Travellers’ Screening Programs in North America and Europe -- t15 Repertoires of Migration Governance in Europe and North America -- tAfterword: Human Mobility Needs Strategic Planning: Moving Beyond Populist and Exploitative Immigration Policies -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMillions of people arrive in North America each year, including highly skilled immigrants and temporary workers, refugees, and international students. Migration, border control, and asylum are ongoing flashpoints in Canadian, American, and Mexican relations, and deeply affect the domestic politics and economies of each country.While migration has emerged as an only increasingly charged topic in public discourse, research has largely focused on North America’s lack of regional integration around mobility, often neglecting aspects of regional cooperation, hierarchy, and global engagement. Migration Governance in North America advances that conversation by examining the complex dynamics of mobilities across the continent through contemporary analysis and historical context. Situating North America within the global migration landscape, contributors from Canada, the United States, Mexico, and Europe unpack such issues as temporary labour mobility, border security, asylum governance, refugee resettlement, and the role of local actors and activists in coping with changing policies and politics.In the wake of a series of significant and likely enduring changes across the continent this flagship volume puts policy developments and migrant organizing in conversation across borders, investigates often contentious domestic, regional, and global migration politics, and reveals how intersecting policy frameworks affect the movement of people.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aImmigrantsxGovernment policyzNorth America. 0aRefugeesxGovernment policyzNorth America. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Immigration.2bisacsh  aCanada.  aEU.  aMexico.  aNAFTA.  aSTCA.  aUNHCR.  aUSMCA.  aUnited Nations.  aUnited States.  aasylum.  aborder control.  acitizenship.  aclimate change.  adevelopment.  adomestic politics.  aexecutive power.  agovernance.  ahuman rights.  aimmigration.  ainternally displaced person.  ainternational organizations.  ainternational protection.  amigrants.  amining.  amobility.  anorms.  apublic policy.  arefugees.  aregimes.  aregionalization.  aresettlement.  atemporary foreign worker.  atransportation.  atravel.  aundocumented.  avisa.1 aBanerjee, Kiran, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBanerjee, Kiran, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCameron, Geoffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoen, Alise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrépeau, François, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDupeyron, Bruno, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerris, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeddes, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGil, Ana Martín, econtributor.4ctb4https://i